Visas &lsquo;weaponised&rsquo;: Gov&rsquo;t denies Hong Kong Free Press editor a work visa, without explanation, after 6-month wait<br />
<br />
<a href="https://hongkongfp.com/2020/08/27/visas-weaponised-govt-denies-hong-kong-free-press-editor-a-work-visa-without-explanation-after-6-month-wait/" data-sr-url="https://r.lihkg.com/link?u=https%3A%2F%2Fhongkongfp.com%2F2020%2F08%2F27%2Fvisas-weaponised-govt-denies-hong-kong-free-press-editor-a-work-visa-without-explanation-after-6-month-wait%2F&d=a8feNXbjtso6d%2BC97Zvpk9XdGXproJJDEW77mXnEmng%3D&h=a5a1c1eb" data-auto-link target="_blank">https://hongkongfp.com/2020/08/27/visas-weaponised-govt-denies-hong-kong-free-press-editor-a-work-visa-without-explanation-after-6-month-wait/</a><br />
<br />
//<span class="red">Hong Kong Free Press&nbsp;has been denied a work visa for an established journalist following an almost 6-month wait.</span>//<br />
<br />
//Editor-in-chief Tom Grundy said that many other news outlets&nbsp;remain in limbo amid unprecedented visa delays, and a pattern had now emerged: &ldquo;We are a local news outlet and our prospective editor was a journalist originally from Ireland, so this is not another tit-for-tat measure under the US-China trade dispute. It appears we have been targeted under the climate of the new security law and because of our impartial, fact-based coverage.&rdquo;//<br />
<br />
//In an emailed response to HKFP on Tuesday, a spokesperson for Immigration did not state why the visa was denied: &ldquo;Hong Kong has always adopted a pragmatic and open policy on the employment of professionals in Hong Kong, allowing those possessing special skills, knowledge or experience of value to and not readily available in Hong Kong to apply to come to work, including journalistic work,&rdquo; they said. They added that each case was processed in accordance with the law.//
